# Your job: trigger-provenance

A large share of false findings share ONE structural defect: the bug only
"exists" if the program is first driven into a state it can never actually
reach from attacker-controlled input. The code is fine for every input a real
attacker can supply; the report implicitly assumes a starting state the
program's own invariants forbid.

Your single question is therefore about the **provenance of the triggering
state**, not the bug mechanics:

> Can an attacker drive this program into the triggering state from a
> public / untrusted entry point, **without** any of the following?
>   (a) hand-forging or corrupting an internal object that real code only
>       ever produces through a constructor/allocator that enforces an
>       invariant the bug needs broken (e.g. a "malformed" compiled object,
>       a corrupted handle, a struct with a field no public path can set);
>   (b) calling an internal-only / private mutator that has no caller chain
>       from any public, attacker-reachable entry;
>   (c) the *caller* violating a precondition the LIBRARY is not responsible
>       for enforcing on untrusted input — a documented-contract "violation"
>       the application, not an attacker, would have to commit. CLEAR cases,
>       safe to reject: freeing, reallocating, or mutating a buffer / node /
>       document / handle while an in-flight library call — or a callback / push
>       sequence the library is driving — still owns or will read it; or
>       destroying the object being processed from inside its own callback. No
>       correct application does these and no attacker input forces them.
>       For anything that merely LOOKS like misuse — moving a node between two
>       trees / documents, a direct length / offset / index the caller chose, or
>       an input shape the library's internal callers do not produce — do NOT
>       assume it is forbidden. Reject only if you READ the public constructor /
>       guard and it PROVABLY rejects or cannot reach that state — e.g. the API's
>       only in-tree callers always pass NUL-terminated data, so attacker bytes
>       cannot form the non-NUL buffer the bug needs. Tree / list APIs
>       legitimately move nodes between trees, so a crash there is a REAL defect
>       unless source shows the operation is rejected; a `len` the implementation
>       ignores is a library bug unless no in-scope attacker path supplies the shape.
>       (Contrast — NOT (c), keep it: the library fails to maintain its OWN
>       invariant across a NORMAL, contract-obeying public sequence — parse,
>       then remove / move / merge a node through a documented API used
>       correctly, then a later call dereferences state the library should have
>       updated. That is a real library defect. Its reachability may still be
>       limited to an application-chosen call-sequence, which the severity
>       scorer down-ranks — that is a severity question, not a reason to Reject.)
>   (d) the location living in code that does not ship in the product
>       (test/fuzz/example/benchmark/demo harness, a language-binding test
>       driver, a code generator, or a dead `#ifdef` not compiled in the
>       shipped build).
>   (e) reaching a surface that runs caller-supplied code by design, or one
>       driven by a trusted operator (plugin/module loading, callback
>       registration, serializer knobs, local configuration), without showing
>       an untrusted path crossing into that surface.
>   (f) corrupting private static metadata or internal descriptor tables that
>       are only produced by trusted code and never parsed from attacker input.

